    title: "Scripts",
    summary: "Keeping your prescriptions organised ensures you can manage your medications e\ufb00ectively and avoid potentially dangerous mistakes. This helps you stay consistent with your doses and makes it easy to tr",
    body: `Keeping your prescriptions organised ensures you can manage your medications eﬀectively and avoid potentially
dangerous mistakes. This helps you stay consistent with your doses and makes it easy to track when you need
refills, so you’re never caught short. An organised system allows you to avoid doubling up on medications,
missing doses, or accidentally taking expired prescriptions.

Having your prescription information handy is also crucial when visiting new doctors or specialists, they’ll need
to know what you’re currently taking to avoid prescribing something that could interact negatively with your
existing medications. This is especially important if you’re managing multiple health conditions.

Other key benefits include:

Easier refills: Staying on top of your refills prevents interruptions in your medication schedule, which is especially
important for chronic conditions.

Emergency preparedness: In case of an emergency, having your scripts easily accessible helps healthcare
providers understand your medical needs and administer care quickly.

Managing side eﬀects: If you experience side eﬀects, having an organised record allows you to quickly share the
information with your doctor to adjust your medication plan.

Family support: If a family member needs to assist with your medication routine, a well-organised system
ensures they know what to do and when to help out.

Start by gathering all your current prescriptions from your doctor, pharmacy, or any recent visits to specialists.
You can also request a list of past and current prescriptions from your pharmacist, who can print out a full
history. Organise this information in a way that makes sense to you.

Make sure to include:

•   Medication name (both brand and generic, if applicable)
•   Dosage and frequency (e.g., 1 tablet, twice daily)
•   Prescribing doctor’s name and contact details
•   Date of prescription and number of refills available
•   Pharmacy contact information

Any notes on side eﬀects or special instructions

Pro tip: Keep a reminder system (e.g., calendar alerts or a refill tracker) so you know when it’s time to renew
your scripts. This also makes it easy to stay proactive and avoid last-minute pharmacy runs. With everything
organised, you’ll be ready to share your medication details with healthcare providers and always stay on top of
your treatment plan.`,
